{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514226"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12299"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12299"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.53,0.06,0.25,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48040"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4819"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32778"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"2088"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48040"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner two weeks after excision of a malignant lesion from the floor of her mouth. She has had ongoing loss of taste since the operation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the patient has symmetrical facial movements and an intact light touch sensation to the face. The gag reflex is intact and there is no deviation when the patient is asked to poke her tongue out. The loss of taste sensation is apparent over the anterior two-thirds of her tongue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following structures is most likely to have been injured during the surgery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inferior alveolar nerve","Lingual nerve","Buccal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient above has likely suffered damage to the \u003Cstrong\u003Elingual nerve\u003C/strong\u003E located at the floor of the mouth. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elingual nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3), and carries special visceral afferent fibres from the \u003Cstrong\u003Echorda tympani \u003C/strong\u003E(branch of the facial nerve, CN VII) to provide sensory innervation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, lingual gingiva and floor of the mouth. The fibres from the chorda tympani are responsible for taste sensation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue in addition to secretomotor function to the submandibular and sublingual salivary glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior alveolar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is not involved in taste sensation, instead providing sensory innervation to the molar and premolar teeth. It is the largest branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve IX) has both motor and sensory function. It provides motor innervation to the stylopharyngeus muscle in addition to secretomotor function of the parotid gland. The pharynx, tonsillar region and posterior one-third of the tongue are sensory innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve. Additionally, it provides taste sensation to the posterior one-third of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebuccal nerve \u003C/strong\u003Ealso branches from the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3). It is sensory in function, conveying general sensation to the skin over the anterior part of the cheek, the mucous membrane of the inner aspect of the cheek and the lateral aspect of the gum adjacent to the molar teeth of the mandible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve XII) is purely motor in function, supplying the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue (with the exception of palatoglossus).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The chorda tympani branch of the facial nerve is responsible for innervating taste sensation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue","The chorda tympani (branch of the facial nerve CN VII) joins the lingual nerve (branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve CN V3) to carry the special visceral afferent fibers from the chorda tympani for taste sensation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue."],"references":["Gibbons JR, Sadiq NM. Neuroanatomy, Neural Taste Pathway. [Updated 2022 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545236/","Keith L. Moore, Arthur F. Dalley. Clinically Oriented Anatomy"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32778"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12299"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32778"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-03T18:38:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-27T20:12:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4819"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48040"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{